AIM

To write a C++ program using an STL container (vector) to insert elements, display them, and perform basic operations such as push, pop, and size retrieval.

ALGORITHM

Start the program.

Include the header file <vector> for using the STL vector container.

Declare a vector of integers.

Use push_back() to insert elements into the vector.

Display the elements of the vector using a loop.

Remove the last element using pop_back().

Display the updated vector.

Print the size of the vector using size().

End the program.

CODE
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    // Declare vector
    vector<int> numbers;

    // Insert elements
    numbers.push_back(10);
    numbers.push_back(20);
    numbers.push_back(30);
    numbers.push_back(40);

    cout << "Elements in the vector: ";
    for (int n : numbers) {
        cout << n << " ";
    }
    cout << endl;

    // Remove the last element
    numbers.pop_back();

    cout << "After pop_back(), vector elements: ";
    for (int n : numbers) {
        cout << n << " ";
    }
    cout << endl;

    // Display size
    cout << "Current size of vector: " << numbers.size() << endl;

    return 0;
}

OUTPUT (Sample)
Elements in the vector: 10 20 30 40
After pop_back(), vector elements: 10 20 30
Current size of vector: 3

RESULT

The program successfully demonstrates the use of the STL vector container in C++.
Operations performed
